1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:03,312
No man can tell of God exactly what he is.

2
00:00:03,262 --> 00:00:07,962
According to St Dionysius, God is not anything we can say or think.

3
00:00:07,962 --> 00:00:18,275
St Augustine cries: ‘I who have ever been in God and ever more shall be, would sooner I had never been and never more should be than that we found a single word that we could say of God.

4
00:00:18,275 --> 00:00:26,012
Were we compelled to speak of God, in that case I should say: Verily, in no sense is God comprehensible nor yet attainable.

5
00:00:26,012 --> 00:00:28,475
God is what thought cannot better.

6
00:00:28,475 --> 00:00:34,012
Nay, I declare God beggars human thought; he transcends all human conception.

7
00:00:34,012 --> 00:00:36,137
No man knows what God is.

8
00:00:36,137 --> 00:00:40,150
Aught that a man could or would think of God, God is not at all.

9
00:00:40,150 --> 00:00:44,312
It is the nature of the soul not to be satisfied except with God.

10
00:00:44,312 --> 00:00:49,350
But all that heart can desire is small, is insignificant compared with God.

11
00:00:49,350 --> 00:00:54,375
Yet man’s thought may be never so rich or so rare but his desire outstrips it.

12
00:00:54,375 --> 00:00:58,975
So he transcends man’s desire as well as transcending human thought.

13
00:00:59,140 --> 00:01:02,090
St Dionysius says, God is naught.

14
00:01:02,040 --> 00:01:05,602
Meaning that God is as incomprehensible as naught.

15
00:01:05,602 --> 00:01:11,465
St Bernard says, I know not what God is; but what I know not that he is that same is he.

16
00:01:11,465 --> 00:01:18,540
A heathen philosopher maintains that what we know of the First Cause is rather what we are ourselves than what the First Cause is.

17
00:01:18,540 --> 00:01:20,827
For that passes understanding.

18
00:01:20,827 --> 00:01:31,602
And in this strain the heathen doctor argues in his book, The Light of Lights, that God is super-essential, super-rational, super-intelligible, i.e. beyond the natural understanding.

19
00:01:31,602 --> 00:01:34,390
I speak not of gracious understanding.

20
00:01:34,390 --> 00:01:42,790
By grace man may be carried to the length of understanding as St Paul understood who was caught up into the third heaven and saw unspeakable things.

21
00:01:42,790 --> 00:01:45,852
He saw, but was not able to express them.

22
00:01:45,852 --> 00:01:50,690
For what a man knows he knows in its cause or in its mode or in its effect.

23
00:01:50,690 --> 00:01:55,065
But in these respects God remains unknown, for he is the first.

24
00:01:55,065 --> 00:01:58,640
Further, he is modeless, i.e. undetermined.

25
00:01:58,640 --> 00:02:03,065
And he is without effect, that is, in his mysterious stillness.

26
00:02:03,065 --> 00:02:06,440
Here he abides apart from the names that are given him.

27
00:02:06,440 --> 00:02:08,315
Moses asked his name.

28
00:02:08,315 --> 00:02:11,015
God answered, He-who-is hath sent thee.

29
00:02:11,015 --> 00:02:13,140
Otherwise he could not tell it.

30
00:02:13,140 --> 00:02:18,427
God as simply being, in that sense he could never give himself to be known to creatures.

31
00:02:18,427 --> 00:02:32,640
Not that he could not do it, but creature could not understand it.—I have often laid it down that God’s lordship does not lie merely in his lordship over creature; his lordship consists in his power to create a thousand worlds and dominate them all in his abstract essence.

32
00:02:32,640 --> 00:02:34,702
Therein lies his lordship.

33
00:02:34,702 --> 00:02:44,640
Dionysius and Gregory both teach that the divine being is not comprehensible in any sense: not to any wit nor any understanding, not even to angelic understanding.

34
00:02:44,640 --> 00:02:53,515
Its simplicity and triplicity is a thing not to be grasped by the human mind even at its best, nor by the angelic mind even at its clearest.

35
00:02:53,515 --> 00:02:59,215
It was said by a philosopher that whoso knows of God that he is unknown, that man knows God.

36
00:02:59,215 --> 00:03:04,990
For it is the height of gnosis and perception to know and understand in agnosia and a-perception.

37
00:03:04,990 --> 00:03:08,252
To know him really is to know him as unknowable.

38
00:03:08,252 --> 00:03:17,465
As the master puts it: If I must speak of God, then I will say, God is something which is in no sense to be reached or grasped; and I know nothing else about him.

39
00:03:17,465 --> 00:03:27,127
According to St Augustine, what we say about God is not true; what we say that God is he is not; what we say he is not that he is rather than what we say that he is.

40
00:03:27,127 --> 00:03:29,652
Nothing we can say of God is true.

41
00:03:29,652 --> 00:03:33,552
God’s worth and God’s perfection cannot be put into words.

42
00:03:33,552 --> 00:03:37,027
When I say man, I have in my mind human nature.

43
00:03:37,027 --> 00:03:40,927
When I say grey, I have in my mind the greyness of grey.

44
00:03:40,927 --> 00:03:46,002
When I say God, I have in my mind neither God’s majesty nor his perfection.

45
00:03:46,002 --> 00:03:51,115
Dionysius insists that the more we can abstract from God the better we shall see him.

46
00:03:51,115 --> 00:03:55,752
God is such that we apprehend him better by negation than by affirmation.

47
00:03:55,752 --> 00:04:04,965
Hence the dictum of one master that to argue about God from likeness is to argue falsely about him, but to argue by denials is to argue about him correctly.

48
00:04:04,965 --> 00:04:13,015
Dionysius says, writing about God, He is super-essential, he is super-luminous; I attribute to him neither this nor that.

49
00:04:13,015 --> 00:04:16,690
For whatever he conceives, God far transcends it.

50
00:04:16,690 --> 00:04:19,177
There is no knowing him by likeness.

51
00:04:19,177 --> 00:04:24,065
Rather by attributing unlikeness may we make some approach to understanding him.

52
00:04:24,065 --> 00:04:25,827
Take an illustration.

53
00:04:25,827 --> 00:04:33,115
Supposing I describe a ship to someone who has never seen one, then looking at a stone he will plainly see that it is not a ship.

54
00:04:33,115 --> 00:04:38,015
And the plainer he sees that it is not ship-like, the more he will know about a ship.

55
00:04:38,015 --> 00:04:39,915
It is the same with God.

56
00:04:39,915 --> 00:04:44,990
The more we can impute to him not-likeness, the nearer do we get to understanding him.

57
00:04:44,990 --> 00:04:48,090
Holy Scripture yields us merely privatives.

58
00:04:48,090 --> 00:04:53,340
That we should credit God with matter, form and work is due to our gross senses.

59
00:04:53,340 --> 00:04:57,652
We fail to find God one because we try to come at him by likeness.

60
00:04:57,652 --> 00:05:04,665
Dionysius cries, ‘Friend Timothy, if thou wouldst catch the spirit of truth pursue it not with the human senses.

61
00:05:04,665 --> 00:05:07,390
It is so swift, it comes rushing.

62
00:05:07,390 --> 00:05:13,265
God is to be sought in opposites: in unknowing knowing shall we know God; in forgetfulness of

63
00:05:13,420 --> 00:05:17,795
ourselves and all things even to the naked essence of the Godhead.

64
00:05:17,745 --> 00:05:21,145
Dionysius was exhorting one of his disciples.

65
00:05:21,145 --> 00:05:29,032
Friend,’ quoth he, ‘cease from all activity and empty thyself of self that thou mayest commune with the Sovran Good, God namely.

66
00:05:29,032 --> 00:05:33,607
Pray God we may seek him so that we shall find him nevermore to lose him.

67
00:05:33,607 --> 00:05:34,495
Amen.

